###Set Up SSH Key Authentication on a Linux Server

##Purpose:
This document outlines the standard procedure for configuring SSH key authentication on a linux server. For this document, we will be using Red Hat Enterprise Linux.

##Audience:
This document is intended for system admins, server admins, and other member of the IT team that are involved in configuring communication with the server.

##Scope:
This document covers the following:
- Preparing a Linux server for remote administration
- Installing SSH
- Configuring SSH, key-based access, basic firewall SSH access, and basic SSH security practices
- Generating and transfering keys
- Verifying SSH services

##Execution Steps:

#Step 1: Aquire Prerequisites and Clearance:
Step 1.1: Identify Server
- Find the server that you want to configure SSH key authentication on.
Step 1.2: Get clearance/login credentials
- Ask the administrator with clearance if you are allowed to configure SSH key authentication on.
- Get a login that is used on the server that has priveleges to configure SSH on the server.
Step 1.3: Get any peripheral devices needed to interface with the server
- You will need a method of interfacing with the server. Options include:
  - Monitor, mouse, and keyboard
  - Console cable, and laptop
  - Rack mounted monitor and keyboard
- The interface method is up to you, but we will be simulating a physical connection with a monitor, mouse, and keyboard using VMWare Workstation.

#Step 2: Set Up Enviroment:
Step 2.1: Connect server with power and all peripherals needed
- Make sure the server has a source of power.
- Connect any peripherals chosen in Step 1.3.
Step 2.2: Turn on server and log in
- Turn on the server and let it boot to the RHEL login screen.
- Log in using the credentials aquired in step 1.2.
Step 2.3: Get to the terminal
- Once logged in, click the search bar at the top center of the screen.
  - If you don't see the search bar, press the red hat icon at the top left of the screen to reveal it.
- Type "terminal", and press enter.

#Step 3: Verifying/Downloading SSH services:
Step 3.1: Verify SSH:
- In the terminal, type "systemctl status sshd.service", and press enter. The output should show you if SSH services are already running on the server.
  - If the output contains the green text "active (running)", that means that SSH services are currently functional, and you can skip to Step 4.
  - If the output doesn't contain the green text, we will have to download the SSH services. This document will show how to do that in the following steps.
Step 3.2: Download SSH:
- Type "yum install openssh-server" into the terminal to download the most recent SSH services
- Type "systemctl start sshd" to start the SSH services.







